result.execSummary:
The defendant Dustin J. Moen was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Manuf/Deliver Amphetamine(<=3g) [Modifiers: Repeater], a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(e)1.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

superMiscConds.notes:
Defendant shall provide a DNA sample.  Defendant shall not possess or consume any controlled substances without a valid prescription.  Defendant shall undergo any counseling as recommended by probation.    Defendant shall pay supervision fees as ordered by the Department of Corrections. 
If probation is ordered and ultimately revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due.  All available enforcement actions will be used.
Defendant shall undergo an AODA and follow through with any recommendations.

records.addlTxt: of Sentencing on Revocation held on April 12, 2016 - Mary P. Bader, RPR

Defendant Dustin J. Moen in court with attorney Alec Phillip Nocco.  Defendant Dustin J. Moen in custody.  Kristi S. Tlusty appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Plea agreement put into the record.  Written waiver of preliminary hearing filed.  Court questions defendant regarding waiving preliminary hearing.  Court questions defendant.  Court finds defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waives right to a preliminary hearing.  Court finds probable cause and binds defendant over for trial.  Information filed.  Waive reading of Information.  Plea of no contest to Count 1.  Plea colloquy.  Plea freely, voluntarily and intelligently; factual basis exists.  Court finds defendant guilty of Count 1.  Count 2 is dismissed and read in.  Statement by attorneys and defendant.  Court orders count 1 - 3 years prison with 1 year of initial confinement and 2 years of extended supervision.  Conditions of extended supervision are court costs; DNA sample and surcharge; no possession or consumption of any controlled substances without a valid prescription; AODA and follow all treatment recommendations and any other counseling as recommended by probation.  Defendant is eligible for Challenge Incarceration Program and Substance Abuse Program - rt
